{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b5b7bb74-b200-4d9f-8f56-699e390ffa19","content":"This is a **TUnit** project, which uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. It uses `--treenode-filter` instead of VSTest's `--filter`. To run only `SmsNotificationTests`:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe treenode filter uses a path-like syntax: `/Assembly/Namespace/Class/Method`. The `**` wildcard matches any assembly/namespace segments, and `/*` at the end matches all test methods in that class.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"c281a539-33f2-457e-b8bd-b98c36e43d15","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively, not VSTest. The filter syntax for MTP with TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` rather than `--filter`.\n\nFor TUnit on MTP, to filter by class name, the treenode filter syntax is:\n\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. TUnit 0.6.120 - this is an older version. Let me check what the correct filter syntax is.\n\nTUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform. For MTP-based runners, the filter is `--treenode-filter` with a path-like syntax. \n\nThe tree node filter format follows a path structure like `/AssemblyName/Namespace/ClassName/MethodName`, where `**` matches any number of segments and `*` matches within a segment. To target all tests in the `SmsNotificationTests` class, I can use the glob-style wildcard pattern with double asterisks to match the assembly and namespace parts before the class name.","outputTokens":516,"requestId":"340F:222DF7:A83AF4:C652F3:69F40217"},"id":"ee46a67f-555a-42fb-b151-52236f4a0fab","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:30:10.863Z","parentId":"e28c7149-136e-4f78-a0f6-f62f0739829c"}
